[normal]1. [bold]Background[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1.
[normal] 
[normal]Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (M.E.) is a fluctuating 
[normal]long-term condition 
[normal]that 
[normal]affects around 250,000 men, women and children in the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]It causes symptoms affecting many body systems, more commonly the nervous and immune systems. 
[normal]Around 25% of patients are severely affected, and may be confined to bed or unable to leave the house without the use of a wheelchair. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]. Action for M.E. is the UK’s largest charity for people affected by M.E.
[normal] 
[normal]We provide information and support, campaign for better services and more effective treatments
[normal], 
[normal]and drive and invest in research.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.
[normal]3
[normal]. Our
[normal] submission 
[normal]focuses on four terms of reference from the Health Select Committee’s inquiry into the management of long-term conditions.
[normal]inquiry into the Management of long-term conditions inquiry into the Management of long-term conditions
[normal] It is 
[normal]based on responses to a 14-question survey for people with M.E. in England, devised by Action for M.E. and publicised via our Online M.E. Centre
[normal] and social media sites
[normal] from 4 to 30 April 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]. 
[normal]The survey was answered by 
[normal]252 
[normal]people with M.E. 
[normal]This was a good response given the short time frame. Results of the survey reflect what we expected and 
[normal]are 
[normal]broadly representativ
[normal]e of people with M.E., with 
[normal]who
[normal] 
[normal]the charity is in daily contact.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal]. 
