[normal]3.1
[normal]3
[normal].
[normal] A respondent in Ipswich told us: 
[normal]“I have been advised by my social worker that they cannot and will not get involved with any care relating to my children and therefore any care provided for me is for me and me alone. This is particularly 
[normal]unhelpful, e
[normal]specially as I am no closer to getting a care package in place for me after making first contact with social services more than six months ago.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.14
[normal].
[normal] A majority of people with M.E. (86% - see paragraph 3.6) told us they have been offered no social care services in the last year. Given the disabling physical symptoms of M.E., and the fact that 25% of patient
[normal]s are severely affected (house- 
[normal]or bed-bound), 
[normal]we believe it is important to have a 
[normal]national approach to improving quality and developing 
[normal]social care
[normal], with specific guidance for specialist conditions such as M.E.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.[bold] [bold]This section refers to t[bold]he interaction between mental health conditions and long-term physical health conditions[bold].[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.
[normal] 
[normal]Living with a long-term condition such as M.E. is no easy task. Some people with M.E. find themselves facing a mental health issue, such as depression or anxiety, as a result. 
[normal]We asked respondents to tell us about their
[normal] experience of this, and 
[normal]217
[normal] did so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2.
[normal] Many respondents spoke of the anxiety, depression and isolation that comes from living with a long-term, fluctuating condition that is still little understood. Some felt that their GP understood this reaction, while others are wary of discussing mental health issues alongside their M.E.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.
[normal] A
[normal] respondent in Greater Manchester said: “I fear saying anything because my GP and healthcare professionals have so many times tried to attribute any symptoms I have down entirely to me being depressed.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]4
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents if their mental health issue was considered separately from their M.E. by their healthcare professional. Of the 
[normal]213
[normal] people who answered this question, 
[normal]23.8% (50 respondents) said this question wasn’t relevant to them. Of the remaining 163 respondents,
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]43.6
[normal]% (71
[normal] respondents) said 
[normal]yes
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]35
[normal]% (57
[normal] respondents) said 
[normal]no
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]21.4
[normal]% (
[normal]35
[normal] resp
[normal]ondents) said they weren’t sure
[normal]4.5
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents to tell us more about their experience of this if they could, and 
[normal]105
[normal] did so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]6
[normal].
[normal] A respondent in West Sussex said: “Sometimes I have felt that healthcare professionals consider my health issues and physical symptoms to be caused by depression or anxiety, which I find extremely frustrating as I feel my anxiety and depression are brought on by the M.E. and not the other way around.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]M.E. is a neurological condition, not a mental health problem. While it is encouraging to see that 43.6% (see paragraph 4.4.) reported that their mental health issue was considered separately from their M.E. by their healthcare professional, just over a third did not, while more than a fifth said they weren’t sure, indicating a lack of clarity in communication 
[normal]from
[normal] their healthcare professional. 
[normal]U
[normal]nderstanding and awareness of M.E. among health professionals 
[normal]must be 
[normal]improved.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.[bold] T[bold]his section refers [bold]to [bold]the [bold]extent to which patients are being[bold] offered personalised services, and patient contribution to better outcomes.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents if they 
[normal]have a care plan based on 
[normal]their
[normal] 
[normal]individual needs. 
[normal]Of the 230
[normal] people who answered this question, 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]87% (200
[normal] respondents) said no
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]7.8% (18
[normal] respondents) said yes
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]5.2% (12
[normal] respondents) said they didn’t know.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents to tell us more about their experience of this if they could, and 
[normal]57 
[normal]did so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal] One respondent in Greater Manchester said: “Since moving to my current address five months ago I have found it very frustrating that my care support plan has not been adhered to. I have received mostly help with domestic tasks and no personal care. It has not addressed my individual needs and has also been too expensive for me to afford, meaning that I have had to cancel care and am now making a formal complaint.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents if they thought that their healthcare professional valued their ideas when it
[normal] came to working out treatment. 
[normal]Of the 
[normal]223
[normal] people who answered this question, 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]37.7% (84 respondents) said yes
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]34.5% (77
[normal] respondents) said no
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]30.9% (69
[normal] respondents) said they weren’t sure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.
[normal] 
[normal]We asked respondents to tell us more about their experience of this if they could, and 
[normal]120 
[normal]did so.
[normal] Some examples of effective patient contribution to better outcomes include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.6
[normal].
[normal] A respondent in Kent said: “The fluctuations and limitations of my illness (dysphonia/sensory sensitivity) make consultations either difficult to attend or very long (always double appointments). So about a year ago my GP provided me with his surgery email address so that I can provide him with updates and relevant research material prior to consultati
[normal]on to inform my on-going care. 
[normal]As a result his knowledge of my illness and support for me has increased and my consultations with him are more constructive.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.7
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Listening to patients 
[normal]as individuals
[normal], as well as through national bodies such as Healthwatch England, is
[normal] key to better patient outcomes.
[normal] Action for M.E. is encouraged to see that more than a third of patients have had this experience – but they are still in the minority. 
[normal]A fundamental shift in attitude is required.
